In ordler to investigate the levels of the potently' carcinogenic benzo/a]pyrene (BP), 31 sam1ples of smoke foods were analysed. The samples tested in- cluded five samples of meal products, three samples of cheese and 22 samples offish. A liquid chromatographic method was developed using a fluorescence detector. BP wvas found in 74% of the samples analysed. The levels varied from not detected to 2.46 pg/kg. Onlv one sample showed a BP level above 1 pg/kg, the maximum level that the EU intends to set for smokedfoods.
